{{See also|Crofting}}
[[Image:Shetland crofthouse museum.jpg|thumb|260px|The [[Shetland]] Crofthouse Museum, with [[peat]] stacked outside]]
A '''croft''' is a [[Agricultural fencing|fenced]] or [[Enclosure|enclosed]] area of land, usually small and [[arable land|arable]], and usually, but not always, with a crofter's [[dwelling]] thereon. A '''crofter''' is one who has [[Land tenure|tenure]] and use of the land, typically as a tenant farmer, especially in rural areas.

== Etymology ==
The word ''croft'' is [[West Germanic languages|West Germanic]] in etymology<ref>From Old English {{lang|ang|croft}}, enclosed field, app. corresp. to Dutch {{lang|nl|kroft}}, {{lang|nl|krocht}}, prominent rocky height, high and dry land, field on the downs. Ulterior etymology unknown. ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', 2nd. ed., 1989</ref> and is now most familiar in [[Scotland]], most crofts being in the [[Highlands and Islands]] area. Elsewhere the expression is generally [[archaism|archaic]]. In [[Scottish Gaelic]], it is rendered {{lang|gd|croit}} ({{IPA-gd|kʰɾɔtʲ|pron}}, plural {{lang|gd|croitean}} {{IPA-gd|ˈkʰɾɔtʲʰən|}}).

Essentially similar positions have been the [[middle Ages|medieval]] ''[[serfdom#Villeins|villein]]''{{Citation needed|date=May 2015}} and the Swedish ''{{lang|sv|[[torp (architecture)|torpare]]}}'' and Norwegian ''{{lang|no|husmenn}}''.

==Legislation==
The [[Scotland|Scottish]] croft is a small [[agriculture|agricultural]] landholding of a type which has been subject to special [[legislation]] applying to the [[Scottish Highlands|Highland region]] of [[Scotland]] since 1886.<ref name="chamberscrofting">{{cite book|title=Chambers's encyclopaedia: a dictionary of universal knowledge for the people|publisher=W. and R. Chambers|page= 575|year=1901|edition=revised|volume=Volume 3|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3zooAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=10 September 2016}}</ref> The legislation was largely a response to the complaints and demands of [[Manorialism|tenant]] families who were victims of the [[Highland Clearances]]. The modern crofters or [[Leasehold estate|tenants]] appear very little in evidence before the beginning of the 18th century. They were tenants at will underneath the [[tacksman]] and [[Mortgage law#Anglo-Saxon and Anglo-Norman law|wadsetters]], but practically their tenure was secure enough. The first evidence that can be found of small tenants holding directly of the [[proprietor]] is in a rental of the estates of Sir D. MacDonald in [[Skye]] and [[North Uist]] in 1715.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}

The first planned crofting townships in the Outer Hebrides were Barragloum and Kirkibost (Great Bernera) which were laid out into 32 large "lots" of between 14 and 30 acres in the uniform rectangular pattern that would become very familiar in later decades. This work was carried out in 1805 by James Chapman for the Earl of Seaforth.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}

The first edition of the Ordnance Survey in 1850 clearly highlights the division of this land and the turf and stone boundaries built by the first tenants in 1805 are still in use today as croft boundaries. Kirkibost was 'cleared' of its tenants in 1823 and the 1850 mapping clearly shows roofless ruins on each parcel of land. The township was however re-settled in 1878 following the Bernera Riot four years earlier using exactly the same division boundaries set out in 1805.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}

The [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] created the [[Crofters' Holdings (Scotland) Act 1886|Crofters' Act 1886]], after the [[Highland Land League]] had gained [[United Kingdom constituencies|seats]] in that parliament. The [[government]] was then [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]], with [[William Ewart Gladstone]] as [[Prime minister|Prime Minister]]. Another Crofters' Act was created in 1993 (the Crofters' (Scotland) Act 1993). The earlier Act established the first [[Crofting Commission]], but its responsibilities were quite different from those of the newer [[Crofters Commission]] created in 1955. The Commission is based in [[Inverness]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}

Crofts held subject to the provisions of the Crofters' Acts are in the [[administrative counties]] of [[Shetland]], [[Orkney]], [[Caithness]], [[Sutherland]], [[Ross-shire]], [[Inverness-shire]] and [[Argyll]], in the north and west of Scotland. Under the 1886 legislation (the [[Crofters' Holdings (Scotland) Act 1886|Crofters' Holdings (Scotland) Act]]) protected crofters are members of a crofters' [[Township (Scotland)|township]], consisting of tenants of neighbouring crofts with a shared right to use [[Common land|common]] [[pasture]]. Since 1976 it has been legally possible for a crofter to acquire title to his croft, thus becoming an [[owner-occupier]].{{citation needed|date=February 2016}}

The [[Land Reform (Scotland) Act 2003]] gives crofters the right to buy their land.

