{{Politics of Maldives}}
A '''constitutional referendum''' was held in the [[Maldives]] on 15 March 1968. The main question was whether to convert the state from a constitutional monarchy under Sultan [[Muhammad Fareed Didi]], to a presidential system. The referendum was the third on the subject; [[Maldivian constitutional referendum, 1952|the first]] in 1952 had seen the state convert to a presidential system, whilst [[Maldivian constitutional referendum, 1953|a second]] in 1953 reversed the decision and saw the monarchy restored in 1954.
The proposals were approved by over 80% of voters,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LclscNCTz9oC&pg=PA820&lpg=PA820&dq=gayoom+election+1983&source=bl&ots=yk7w-a0b5_&sig=EvyivH-QqubD5t14mlftLHpayp8&hl=en&ei=rsd4TcW6H5SIhQeaqfnxBg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CC8Q6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=gayoom%20election%201983&f=false Far East and Australasia 2003] Eur, p820</ref> and a republic was declared on 11 November that year. Prime Minister [[Ibrahim Nasir]] would become [[President of Maldives|president]].
