{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2014}} {{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=Octane Fitness, LLC v. ICON Health & Fitness, Inc. |ArgueDate=February 26 |ArgueYear=2014 |DecideDate=April 29 |DecideYear=2014 |FullName=Octane Fitness, LLC, Petitioner v. ICON Health & Fitness, Inc. |USVol=572 |USPage=___ |ParallelCitations=134 S. Ct. 1749; 188 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 816; 2014 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 3107; 82 U.S.L.W. 4330; 110 [[U.S.P.Q.2d]] 1337 |Docket=12-1184 |OralArgument=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2013/12-1184 |OpinionAnnouncement=https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/13pdf/12-1184_gdhl.pdf |Prior=2011 WL 3900975 ([[D. Minn.]] Sept. 6, 2011); affirmed, 496 [[Fed. Appx.]] 57 ([[Fed. Cir.]] 2012); [[Certiorari|cert.]] granted, 134 S.Ct. 49 (2013) |Subsequent= |Holding= |SCOTUS=2010–2016 |Majority=Sotomayor |JoinMajority=Roberts, Kennedy, Thomas, Ginsburg, Breyer, Alito, Kagan (in full); Scalia (all except footnotes 1-3) |LawsApplied= }} '''''Octane Fitness, LLC v. ICON Health & Fitness, Inc.''''', 572 U.S. ___ (2014),<ref name=SCOTUSdec>{{ussc|name=Octane Fitness, LLC v. ICON Health & Fitness, Inc.|volume=572|year=2014|docket=12-1184}}.</ref> is one of two [[U.S. Supreme Court]] decisions issued on April 29, 2014 regarding patent lawsuit [[American rule (attorney's fees)|fee-shifting]] (the other case being ''Highmark v. Allcare Health''). The Supreme Court essentially made it easier for courts to make the loser pay for all attorney costs, if the lawsuit is regarded as frivolous. In other words, "the Supreme Court's decision grants judges more leeway to crack down on baseless claims."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/4/29/5665364/supreme-court-decision-makes-patent-fee-shifting-easier|title=Supreme Court decision makes it easier to stick patent trolls with court costs|last=Robertson|first=Adi|date=April 29, 2014|work=The Verge|accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref> The decision is particularly relevant for the so-called [[patent troll]]s, which "will have to add a new variable to their calculations before pursuing a marginal lawsuit over their intellectual property: The other side’s legal fees."<ref name=forbes>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/danielfisher/2014/04/29/patent-trolls-face-higher-risks-as-supreme-court-loosens-fee-shifting-rule/|title=Patent Trolls Face Higher Risks As Supreme Court Loosens Fee-Shifting Rule|last=Fisher|first=Daniel|date=April 29, 2014|work=Forbes|accessdate=May 4, 2014}}</ref> The decision was unanimous, with the opinion written by Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]].<ref name=forbes/>
==Background== In the underlying litigation [[ICON Health & Fitness]], the world's largest maker of [[exercise equipment]],<ref>{{cite news | title = Poll: Americans are spending less on exercise | date = 2009-10-19 | publisher = NBCNews.com | work = [[MSNBC]]}}</ref> sued Octane Fitness, a relatively small and specialized maker of [[elliptical trainer]]s, for patent infringement. Octane Fitness, arguing that their elliptical products did not infringe ICON's patent, won on summary judgment and later moved for reimbursement for their attorney's fees. The district court denied the motion for attorney's fees, stating that even though Octane Fitness eventually prevailed, ICON's claims were not objectively baseless,<ref name=SCOTUSdec/>{{rp|5–6}} but the Supreme Court reversed this decision.
